(16, 19, E'# PickupFarm - Community Pre-order Hub for Local Farmers\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nPickupFarm is a community-centered pre-order platform built specifically for small organic farmers who sell at 2-5 farmers markets. The product bridges the gap between the traditional CSA model (rigid, subscription-heavy) and the walk-up farmers market (unpredictable, waste-prone) by offering a flexible weekly pre-order window with neighborhood pickup hubs. Farmers gain cashflow predictability and reduced market labor; customers get priority access to seasonal produce with the convenience of a local pickup.\n\n**Positioning**: Not a CSA. Not a marketplace. A weekly pre-order window that turns loyal market shoppers into reliable direct customers.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source |\n|--------|-------|--------|\n| US small organic farms | ~130,000 | USDA 2023 |\n| Annual local food consumer spending | $20B | FMI 2023 |\n| % farmers using any digital ordering tool | <18% | USDA NASS |\n| Avg produce waste per market event | 18% of inventory | Farm Bureau |\n| CSA member retention rate (year 2) | 55-65% | Rodale Institute |\n| Consumers preferring flexible over fixed box | 71% | FMI Consumer Trends |\n| Willingness to pay premium for pre-order convenience | 12-18% price premium | Nielsen Local Food Study |\n| Estimated tool revenue opportunity (TAM) | $78M/yr | 130k farms × ~$600 |\n\n**Insight**: The CSA model has a retention problem because customers resent locked-in commitments and surprise boxes. Flexible weekly pre-order captures the same demand with 30% better retention.\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Product | Positioning | Price/mo | Key Gap for Farmers |\n|---------|------------|----------|--------------------|\n| Barn2Door | Full farm direct sales platform | $99-$299 | Too expensive, too complex for small farms |\n| Local Line | Farm wholesale + retail | $79-$249 | B2B focused, not community pickup native |\n| Farmigo | CSA management | $50-$150 | Rigid CSA model, dated UX |\n| Harvie | Consumer-facing marketplace | Revenue share | Platform dependency, not farmer-owned channel |\n| Square Online | General e-commerce | $29+ | No pickup routing, no farm-specific logic |\n| **PickupFarm** | **Community pre-order** | **$25-$69** | **Pickup-hub native, flexible ordering, low cost** |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n### Persona A: Tom - The Transitioning Market Farmer\n- **Age**: 51, male, Pacific Northwest\n- **Situation**: Has sold at the same Saturday market for 9 years, has loyal regulars but is physically exhausted by the weekly grind\n- **Core frustration**: Loyal customers buy from him every week but he has no way to notify them when special items are available or when he''ll miss a market\n- **What he wants**: A way to let his "regulars" place orders in advance so he can plan harvest quantities, not just guess\n- **Tech level**: Low-moderate; uses a flip phone for calls, tablet for email\n- **Price sensitivity**: High - would pay $25-$35/month if it replaced one market trip monthly\n\n### Persona B: Jess - The Young Farmer Building a Brand\n- **Age**: 29, female, Hudson Valley NY\n- **Situation**: Second-year farmer with strong Instagram following (4,200 followers) but inconsistent revenue\n- **Core frustration**: Instagram followers say they love her farm but don''t know how to buy from her without showing up to market\n- **What she wants**: A pre-order link she can post on Instagram; a simple storefront that matches her aesthetic\n- **Tech level**: High; comfortable with Shopify-style tools\n- **Price sensitivity**: Medium - values design quality, would pay $50/month for a beautiful customer-facing page\n\n### Persona C: Ray & Linda - Husband-Wife Farm Team\n- **Age**: 47 & 45, rural Ohio\n- **Situation**: Run a 20-acre diversified farm, 4 markets, 2 employees during peak season\n- **Core frustration**: Coordinating which employee goes to which market with which product mix is chaotic; pre-orders would let them pack boxes the night before instead of guessing\n- **What they want**: Multi-location pickup management, packing lists auto-generated per location\n- **Willingness to pay**: $65-$80/month for multi-location features\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|----------|---------|-------------|\n| P0 | Weekly listing builder | Farmer creates weekly available items with quantities, prices, photos |\n| P0 | Public order page | Clean, mobile-optimized page customers access via link or QR |\n| P0 | Pickup hub management | Create and manage multiple pickup locations with schedules |\n| P0 | Order cutoff automation | System closes orders at farmer-set deadline, sends summary |\n| P0 | Packing list generation | Sorted by item and by pickup location for efficient packing |\n| P1 | Customer notification emails | Announce new weekly listings to registered customers |\n| P1 | Stripe payment at checkout | Secure prepayment, reduces no-shows by 85% |\n| P1 | Repeat order memory | Customers can reorder last week''s selection in one click |\n| P1 | Inventory hold system | 5-min cart hold prevents overselling popular items |\n| P2 | Demand heatmap | Visual map of which neighborhoods order most |\n| P2 | SMS pickup reminders | Auto-text customers 2hrs before pickup window |\n| P2 | Seasonal subscription tiers | Optional weekly/biweekly subscription for core customers |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n```\nFrontend:\n  - Farmer admin: React 18 + TailwindCSS (SPA, mobile responsive)\n  - Customer order page: Next.js 15 (SSG with ISR weekly refresh)\n  - QR code generator: Built-in for linking physical market materials\n\nBackend:\n  - API: Go + Echo v4\n  - Scheduled jobs: Cron for cutoff enforcement, reminder dispatch\n  - Payments: Stripe Connect Express\n\nDatabase:\n  - PostgreSQL 16 (core data)\n  - Redis (inventory hold locks, session state)\n\nNotifications:\n  - SendGrid (weekly listing announcements, order receipts)\n  - Twilio (SMS reminders - P1)\n\nHosting:\n  - Railway.app (backend + DB, simple deployment)\n  - Vercel (Next.js frontend)\n```\n\n**Design Principle**: The customer-facing order page must work flawlessly on a 4-year-old Android phone with slow rural LTE. Target <2s first contentful paint, offline-tolerant checkout flow.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Tier | Monthly Price | Key Limits | Best For |\n|------|--------------|------------|----------|\n| Sprout (free) | $0 | 1 location, 15 orders/week | Testing the concept |\n| Grower | $25/mo | 3 locations, 100 orders/week | 1-2 market farmers |\n| Harvest | $49/mo | 8 locations, unlimited orders | 3-5 market farmers |\n| Producer | $79/mo | Unlimited + API + wholesale | Scaling operations |\n| Transaction fee | 1.5% of order value | Included in all plans | Revenue alignment |\n\n**Unit Economics**:\n- CAC target: <$80 (via farmers market association partnerships)\n- LTV at Harvest plan: $49 × 18mo avg = $882\n- LTV:CAC ratio: 11:1\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Milestone | Timeframe | Key Deliverables | Success Gate |\n|-----------|-----------|-----------------|-------------|\n| M1: Core ordering | Month 1 | Listing builder, public order page, packing list export | 10 farms in beta |\n| M2: Payments | Month 2 | Stripe Connect, order confirmation flow | Zero failed payments |\n| M3: Customer retention | Month 3 | Email announcements, repeat order, inventory hold | 40% repeat order rate |\n| M4: Scale | Month 4-5 | Analytics, SMS, referral program launch | 60 paying farms |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | 3-Month Target | 6-Month Target |\n|-----|---------------|----------------|\n| Registered farms | 100 | 300 |\n| Active paid farms | 40 | 150 |\n| MRR | $1,500 | $6,500 |\n| Avg orders/farm/week | 35 | 55 |\n| Customer no-show rate | <8% | <5% |\n| Farmer churn rate | <12%/mo | <8%/mo |\n| NPS (farmers) | ≥40 | ≥50 |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Impact | Probability | Mitigation |\n|------|--------|-------------|------------|\n| Farmers revert to manual methods after trial | High | High | Dedicated onboarding + weekly check-in call for first 30 days |\n| No-show customers damaging farmer trust | High | Medium | Enforce prepayment as default; offer no-show fee policy templates |\n| Rural connectivity issues for customers | Medium | Medium | Offline-capable checkout, SMS confirmation fallback |\n| Seasonality causing winter revenue dip | Medium | High | Promote year-round use cases (eggs, storage crops, value-added products) |\n| Stripe Connect identity verification delays | Low | Medium | Pre-warn farmers, offer manual payout alternative during verification |',
    E'[{"step":"Core differentiation","decision":"Position against both CSA and marketplace models","reason":"CSA has a rigidity problem and marketplace has a platform-dependency problem; the flexible pre-order fills the gap neither solves"},{"step":"Pricing anchor","decision":"$25 Grower plan as primary entry point","reason":"Must be below $30 to remove financial risk perception for farmers skeptical of SaaS tools; upsell path to $49 is natural as they grow"},{"step":"Customer page design","decision":"Next.js SSG for customer-facing order page","reason":"Farmers share this link on Instagram and at markets; must load instantly on mobile without requiring an account"},{"step":"No-show problem","decision":"Default to prepayment, not pay-at-pickup","reason":"Pay-at-pickup creates 15-25% no-show rates that damage farmer trust in the platform; prepayment is the industry standard fix"},{"step":"Go-to-market","decision":"Partner with farmers market associations first","reason":"Each association is a pre-validated cluster of target users; a letter of endorsement unlocks 20-50 farms at once"},{"step":"MVP scope","decision":"Ship without SMS in M1","reason":"Email notifications cover 90% of reminder use case; SMS adds Twilio cost and compliance overhead better handled after revenue validation"}]',
    'submitted', 31, NOW() - INTERVAL '14 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '15 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '14 days'),

