(16, 28, E'# FarmWindow - Zero-Waste Pre-order for Farmers Market Vendors\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nFarmWindow eliminates the guesswork of farmers market selling by giving small organic farms a weekly pre-order window before harvest. Farmers post what''s available Sunday-Tuesday; customers order by Wednesday noon; farmers harvest and pack Thursday; customers pick up Friday-Saturday at community hubs or the market itself. This model reduces produce waste by an estimated 35-50%, improves weekly cashflow predictability, and allows farmers to redirect energy from market logistics to growing.\n\n**The problem in one sentence**: Farmers are growing blind — they harvest based on guesses, drive to markets hoping customers show up, and dump unsold food that took months to grow.\n\n**FarmWindow solves this** by inserting a 72-hour pre-order window between field and market, giving farmers real demand data before they pick a single head of lettuce.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Dimension | Data Point | Implication |\n|-----------|------------|-------------|\n| Active farmers markets in US | 8,600 | Large install base |\n| Avg vendors per market | 35 | ~300,000 farmer-market relationships |\n| Small organic farms (<50 acres) | ~130,000 | Core target |\n| Annual food waste per small farm | $8,000-$22,000 | Strong pain |\n| Direct-to-consumer farm sales (US) | $3.2B/yr | Growing 9% CAGR |\n| Farmers using digital pre-order tools | <5% | Blue ocean |\n| Consumer interest in local pre-order | 68% positive intent | FMI 2023 |\n| Platform TAM | ~$78M/yr | ~130k farms × $600/yr |\n\n**Regulatory tailwind**: USDA Local Food Promotion Program grants ($1M+/yr available) are increasingly funding digital infrastructure for local food systems — FarmWindow fits as a grantable tool.\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | Core Model | Monthly Cost | Primary Weakness |\n|-----------|-----------|-------------|------------------|\n| Barn2Door | Farm website + direct sales | $99-$299 | Too expensive, requires marketing skill |\n| Local Line | Wholesale + retail ordering | $79-$249 | Designed for volume, not community pickup |\n| Farmigo | CSA management platform | $50-$150 | Rigid subscription model, poor mobile UX |\n| Harvie | Consumer marketplace | 10% commission | Platform dependency, customer is Harvie''s not farmer''s |\n| Open Food Network | Open-source collective | Free (self-host) | Technical setup barrier, no support |\n| **FarmWindow** | **Pre-order + pickup routing** | **$19-$69** | **New entrant (brand trust building)** |\n\n**Why we win**: The 72-hour pre-order window is a specific workflow that none of the above natively optimize for. We build the entire product around this one insight.\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n### Persona A: Carol - The Burned-Out Market Regular\n- **Profile**: 58, female, Iowa, 15-acre vegetable farm, 3 markets/week for 12 years\n- **Situation**: Physically cannot sustain the market pace but needs the income; looking for a way to reduce market days without losing revenue\n- **Ideal outcome**: Replace 1-2 market days per week with pre-order pickup revenue, same total income with less driving\n- **Tech comfort**: Low; needs phone-based setup in under 30 minutes\n- **Quote**: "I don''t need fancy. I need something my customers can use without calling me for help."\n\n### Persona B: Derek - The Data-Curious New Farmer\n- **Profile**: 34, male, Georgia, 3rd year farmer, 2 markets, strong online presence\n- **Situation**: Wants to make smarter planting decisions; currently grows based on gut feeling\n- **Ideal outcome**: Use pre-order demand data to decide what to plant each season, reduce guesswork\n- **Tech comfort**: High; builds spreadsheets, uses Notion for planning\n- **Specific need**: Export order history to CSV for his own analysis, week-over-week trend data\n\n### Persona C: The Pickup Hub Host - Michelle\n- **Profile**: 45, female, coffee shop owner who serves as a neighborhood pickup point\n- **Situation**: Hosts weekly farm pickup in her shop, brings in foot traffic, wants a streamlined notification process\n- **Need**: Simple dashboard to see how many pickups are coming and when, automated customer reminders so she isn''t the point of contact\n- **Insight**: Pickup hosts are underserved stakeholders who, if equipped with good tools, become powerful evangelists for the platform\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|----------|---------|-------------|\n| P0 | Pre-order listing (Sunday-Tuesday) | Farmer posts items with quantity caps; listing auto-closes at farmer-set deadline |\n| P0 | Customer order portal | Public link, no account required to order, mobile-first |\n| P0 | Pickup location scheduler | Multiple hub support with address, hours, contact |\n| P0 | Harvest-ready packing list | Auto-sorted by item and pickup location, downloadable PDF |\n| P0 | Order confirmation emails | Instant confirmation to customer and farmer |\n| P1 | Stripe prepayment | Collect payment at order time, farmer payout on pickup day |\n| P1 | Customer account (optional) | Save addresses, order history, one-click reorder |\n| P1 | Hub host dashboard | Simplified view for pickup location hosts |\n| P1 | Weekly listing template | Copy last week''s listing as a starting point |\n| P2 | Planting demand signals | Aggregate order data into crop planning recommendations |\n| P2 | USDA grant report export | Pre-formatted output for Local Food Promotion Program reporting |\n| P2 | Multi-farm bundle orders | Customer orders from 2-3 farms in one checkout (shared pickup) |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n```\nSystem Design:\n\nFrontend:\n  - Farmer dashboard: Next.js 15 + TailwindCSS\n    - Listing builder with drag-to-reorder\n    - Packing list view optimized for printing on 8.5x11\n  - Customer order portal: Static-first with client hydration\n    - Target <1.5s LCP on mobile\n    - Cart holds via Redis with 10-minute expiry\n\nBackend:\n  - REST API: Go + Echo v4\n  - Cron jobs: Cutoff enforcement, reminder emails, payout triggers\n  - Payments: Stripe Connect Express (farmer KYC handled by Stripe)\n\nData:\n  - PostgreSQL 16: farms, listings, orders, pickup locations, customers\n  - Redis: cart locks, rate limiting, session tokens\n\nIntegrations:\n  - SendGrid: transactional email (confirmation, reminders, weekly listing blast)\n  - Twilio: optional SMS confirmation\n  - Stripe: payment processing + Connect payouts\n\nDeployment:\n  - Backend: Fly.io (auto-scaling, low ops overhead)\n  - Frontend: Vercel\n  - DB: Managed PostgreSQL (Supabase or Neon)\n```\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Plan | Price | Allowances | Revenue Source |\n|------|-------|------------|----------------|\n| Free | $0/mo | 1 hub, 20 orders/week | Customer acquisition |\n| Grower | $19/mo | 3 hubs, 75 orders/week | Subscription |\n| Harvest | $49/mo | 10 hubs, unlimited orders | Subscription |\n| Co-op | $69/mo | Unlimited + multi-farm bundle | Subscription |\n| Processing fee | 1.0% + Stripe | Per paid order | Transaction |\n\n**Why 1.0% not 2.9%**: Farmers are margin-thin. A low processing fee with a slightly higher subscription creates better farmer trust than feeling "taxed" on every sale.\n\n**USDA Grant Angle**: Position FarmWindow as grant-eligible infrastructure; offer co-branded grant application assistance to farmers market associations. This opens a B2B2F (business-to-association-to-farmer) channel.\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Phase | Duration | Focus | Gate Metric |\n|-------|----------|-------|-------------|\n| M1: Core pre-order loop | 5 weeks | Listing → order → packing list | 8 farms in beta |\n| M2: Payments + hub | 3 weeks | Stripe Connect, hub host view | First paid transaction |\n| M3: Customer retention | 4 weeks | Accounts, reorder, email blasts | 35% repeat order rate |\n| M4: Analytics + growth | 4-6 weeks | Demand signals, referral loop | 50 paying farms |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | 3 Months | 6 Months |\n|-----|----------|----------|\n| Registered farms | 80 | 250 |\n| Paid subscriptions | 30 | 120 |\n| MRR | $900 | $4,800 |\n| Orders processed/week | 800 | 4,000 |\n| Avg farm produce waste reduction | 30% | 40% |\n| Customer repeat order rate | 35% | 50% |\n| Farmer NPS | ≥42 | ≥52 |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Severity | Probability | Response |\n|------|----------|-------------|----------|\n| Farmers resist committing to pre-order model | High | High | Offer hybrid mode: pre-orders + walk-up; don''t force 100% commitment |\n| Pickup hub hosts drop out | Medium | Medium | Build hub-host incentive (small revenue share or recognition program) |\n| Rural broadband gaps for farmers | Medium | Medium | SMS-based listing creation as fallback; CSV upload support |\n| Produce quality complaints (ordered vs. received) | Medium | Low | Photo upload per listing, quality guarantee policy templates |\n| Stripe Connect verification blocking payouts | Medium | Medium | Clear onboarding instructions, dedicated support for verification issues |',
    E'[{"step":"Core concept","decision":"Build around the 72-hour pre-order window as the defining product mechanic","reason":"This specific workflow (post Sunday, close Wednesday, harvest Thursday, pickup Saturday) is the key value driver and no competitor optimizes for it"},{"step":"Persona expansion","decision":"Include pickup hub hosts as a distinct persona","reason":"Hub hosts are underserved but critical to the network - equipping them well turns them into distribution evangelists at zero CAC"},{"step":"Pricing","decision":"$19 entry plan, 1.0% transaction fee","reason":"Farmer trust is fragile on pricing; 1.0% fee feels fair vs. 2.9% which feels punitive; lower subscription entry removes trial barrier"},{"step":"USDA grant angle","decision":"Build USDA grant reporting export into P2","reason":"Unlocks B2B2F distribution through farmers market associations who need grant reporting; differentiates from all competitors"},{"step":"Technical decision","decision":"Static-first customer order portal with client hydration","reason":"Rural customers on slow connections must not face loading barriers; pre-rendered HTML ensures the page works even on 3G"},{"step":"Hybrid model","decision":"Allow hybrid pre-order + walk-up mode","reason":"Farmers won''t abandon markets on day one; hybrid reduces adoption friction by not requiring a full behavior change upfront"}]',
    'submitted', 53, NOW() - INTERVAL '10 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '11 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '10 days');

