-- IDEA 18: Restaurant Review Booster - Author 22
-- ============================================================
(18, 22, E'# ReputationPlate - Reputation Management Built for Restaurant Owners, Not Marketers\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nReputationPlate is a reputation management tool built around a simple truth: restaurant owners don''t have time to be marketers. The product does one thing better than anything else on the market — it turns the natural end-of-meal moment into a consistent review-generation machine, using printed QR table cards that require zero ongoing effort from the owner after initial setup. The auto-response engine suggests review replies in the owner''s voice (trained over time), and the sentiment dashboard spots recurring complaints before they become patterns.\n\n**Core Design Principle**: Every feature must work while the owner is in the kitchen, not sitting at a desk.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Figure | Basis |\n|--------|--------|-------|\n| Independent restaurants in US | ~500,000 | NRA 2023 |\n| Avg independent: Google reviews | ~35 | BrightLocal |\n| Avg chain location: Google reviews | 150-400 | Industry estimate |\n| Revenue impact of going 3.9 → 4.4 stars | +12-18% covers | HBS + Yelp research |\n| Restaurant owners citing "no time" for reviews | 78% | Owner survey N=200 |\n| Current tool usage among independents | <15% | Industry estimate |\n| Competitor avg price (Podium, Birdeye) | $299-$599/mo | Public pricing |\n| Underserved price tier (<$150/mo) | Largely empty | Market gap |\n\n**The "no time" insight is the product brief**: Every feature decision must start with "can the owner do this in under 2 minutes?"\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Product | Price/mo | Setup Complexity | Restaurant-specific? | QR table flow? |\n|---------|----------|-----------------|---------------------|---------------|\n| Podium | $399-$599 | High (SMS campaigns) | No | No |\n| Birdeye | $299-$499 | High | No | No |\n| Broadly | $199-$299 | Medium | No | No |\n| NiceJob | $75-$149 | Low | No | No |\n| ReviewBuzz | $89-$179 | Medium | No | No |\n| **ReputationPlate** | **$59-$129** | **Very low (setup service)** | **Yes** | **Yes (core)** |\n\n**Summary**: No current product under $150/month offers a QR table flow, restaurant-specific templates, or sentiment analysis. ReputationPlate occupies this empty quadrant.\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n### Persona A: Dave - The "I Just Cook" Owner\n- **Age**: 55, male, Nashville TN\n- **Restaurant**: BBQ joint, 11 years, 4.2 stars, 68 reviews\n- **Attitude toward technology**: Deeply skeptical; uses a cash register, not a POS\n- **Core need**: Something that works without him having to do anything after the first setup\n- **Trigger moment**: His nephew pointed out that the chain BBQ place across town has 840 reviews and shows up first on Google Maps\n- **Requirement**: Can be explained in one sentence and set up in one afternoon\n- **Willingness to pay**: $59-$79/month if it genuinely requires no ongoing maintenance\n\n### Persona B: Nina - The Detail-Oriented Cafe Owner\n- **Age**: 39, female, Seattle WA\n- **Restaurant**: Specialty coffee + light bites, 4.7 stars, 210 reviews, 3 years open\n- **Situation**: Good reviews but notices recurring theme: "slow service on weekends" — wants to catch these patterns before they become a public narrative\n- **Specific need**: Sentiment theme tracking to identify operational blind spots\n- **Tech level**: High; runs the cafe like a startup (uses Notion, Slack, analytics)\n- **Willingness to pay**: $109-$129/month for sentiment + competitive benchmarking\n\n### Persona C: Roberto - The Pizza Chain Wannabe\n- **Age**: 43, male, Phoenix AZ\n- **Restaurants**: 2 pizza locations (opened second 8 months ago)\n- **Problem**: Second location is 3.9 stars vs. 4.5 at the original; can''t figure out what''s different\n- **Need**: Side-by-side review theme comparison across locations\n- **Willingness to pay**: $149/month for multi-location comparison\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|----------|---------|-------------|\n| P0 | White-glove QR card setup | Team designs and ships physical QR table cards to restaurant |\n| P0 | Satisfaction filter | 4-5 star → Google; 1-3 star → private owner inbox |\n| P0 | Private feedback inbox | Captures unhappy customer messages; owner replies to resolve |\n| P0 | Google review sync | Auto-pull all Google reviews into dashboard |\n| P0 | 1-click response templates | Categorized by review type; one click to load, minor edit, post |\n| P1 | Sentiment theme tracker | Auto-tag review keywords into themes (food, service, wait, value) |\n| P1 | Voice-trained response drafts | AI learns owner writing style from approved responses; drafts match voice |\n| P1 | Negative review instant alert | SMS/email when a ≤2 star review is posted |\n| P1 | Yelp + TripAdvisor sync | Expand monitoring beyond Google |\n| P2 | Multi-location side-by-side | Compare sentiment themes across 2+ locations |\n| P2 | Recurring complaint alerts | Alert when same theme appears 3+ times in 30 days |\n| P2 | Review milestone celebrations | Dashboard alert when hitting 50, 100, 250 review milestones |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n```\nCore Systems:\n\nReview Ingestion:\n  - Google Business Profile API (OAuth 2.0)\n  - Yelp Fusion API (read-only)\n  - TripAdvisor (scraping or partner API - P1)\n  - Ingestion cron: Every 30 minutes for active restaurants\n\nQR Landing Page:\n  - Pure HTML/CSS served from Cloudflare CDN\n  - Zero JS dependencies\n  - Target: <600ms load on 3G mobile\n  - Satisfaction rating (1-5 stars) → conditional routing\n\nSentiment Engine:\n  - OpenAI GPT-4o-mini for theme classification\n  - Classify into: food_quality, service_speed, service_attitude,\n    ambiance, value, cleanliness, wait_time\n  - Batch process nightly for cost efficiency\n\nResponse Assistant:\n  - Vector DB (pgvector) stores owner''s approved responses\n  - New review → find similar past responses → generate draft in owner''s style\n  - Owner edit + approve before posting via Google API\n\nInfrastructure:\n  - Backend: Go + Echo v4 on Fly.io\n  - Frontend: Next.js 15 + Tailwind on Vercel\n  - Database: PostgreSQL 16 + pgvector extension\n  - Cache: Redis\n  - Alerts: SendGrid + Twilio\n```\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Plan | Price | Locations | Highlights |\n|------|-------|-----------|------------|\n| Essential | $59/mo | 1 | QR setup, gate, Google sync, response templates |\n| Pro | $99/mo | 1 | + Yelp, sentiment tracker, AI voice drafts, instant alerts |\n| Multi | $149/mo | Up to 4 | Pro + side-by-side location comparison |\n| Physical cards | $29 | 10-pack | Replacement QR cards |\n\n**White-glove setup**: Included in first month for all paid plans. Team designs branded QR cards, ships them, and schedules a 20-minute onboarding call. This is not a cost center — it''s retention insurance (restaurants who receive physical cards and a call have 3x lower 90-day churn).\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Phase | Duration | Deliverables | Gate |\n|-------|----------|-------------|------|\n| M1: The table flow | 4 weeks | QR landing, satisfaction gate, Google sync, response templates | 10 beta restaurants, ≥5 reviews generated/restaurant |\n| M2: Dashboard + alerts | 3 weeks | Review dashboard, negative review alerts, private inbox | Owner login ≥4x/week |\n| M3: Intelligence | 5 weeks | Sentiment tagging, AI drafts, Yelp sync | 60% owner response rate |\n| M4: Grow | 4 weeks | Billing, referral program, multi-location | 45 paying restaurants |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | 3-Month | 6-Month |\n|-----|---------|--------|\n| Paying restaurants | 45 | 180 |\n| MRR | $4,000 | $16,000 |\n| Avg monthly new reviews per restaurant | 10 (vs. 3 before) | 15 |\n| Avg star rating improvement (3-month cohort) | +0.2 | +0.3 |\n| Owner response rate | ≥55% | ≥70% |\n| 90-day restaurant retention | ≥75% | ≥80% |\n| Net Promoter Score | ≥50 | ≥60 |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Severity | Probability | Mitigation |\n|------|----------|-------------|------------|\n| Physical card logistics add complexity | Medium | Medium | Partner with local print-and-ship service; pre-print standard designs |\n| Google API quota limits at scale | High | Medium | Implement request batching; apply for higher quota tier proactively |\n| Restaurant owners ignore private feedback inbox | Medium | High | Weekly digest summarizes feedback; mobile push when new message arrives |\n| Competitor drops price to undercut | Medium | Low | White-glove service and physical cards create switching cost that price alone can''t overcome |\n| Voice-trained AI sounds off-brand | Low | Medium | Owner reviews 5 sample drafts before "style lock"; reset option available anytime |',
    E'[{"step":"Core design principle","decision":"Everything must work while the owner is in the kitchen","reason":"Restaurant owners don''t have desk jobs; any feature requiring 15+ minutes of focused attention will be abandoned; the product must run itself"},{"step":"Physical cards strategy","decision":"White-glove card setup included in first month","reason":"Physical cards are the highest-leverage activation moment; restaurants that receive and display cards generate 4x more reviews than those that don''t; this is retention insurance not a cost"},{"step":"AI voice training","decision":"Vector-based owner style learning from approved responses","reason":"Generic AI responses are detectable and damage credibility; building a restaurant-specific response voice creates long-term stickiness that competitors can''t easily replicate"},{"step":"Pricing anchor","decision":"$59 Essential as lowest tier","reason":"Podium at $399 has set a false floor; $59 is low enough to feel like a no-brainer trial for a restaurant generating $800k+ revenue, while still being profitable at scale"},{"step":"Sentiment engine","decision":"Batch nightly processing to control OpenAI costs","reason":"Real-time sentiment on every review would cost $0.10-$0.30/review; nightly batch reduces this 10x while still providing next-day actionable data"},{"step":"Competitive differentiation","decision":"QR table flow + physical cards + restaurant-specific templates as the three-part moat","reason":"Each element alone is copyable; all three together require operational investment that large enterprise players won''t make for the SMB segment"}]',
    'submitted', 45, NOW() - INTERVAL '16 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '17 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '16 days');

